{"summary":"All three amendments address real defects confirmed by code inspection: the timeout buffer can panic on `Duration` overflow, timeout/cancel only kills the direct child instead of the spawned process tree, and retry backoff can leave a crashed run stranded in a non-resumable `Running` snapshot.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-13-787f9c72","decision":"accept","rationale":"`src/contexts/agent_execution/service.rs` computes `request.timeout + Duration::from_secs(30)` when the adapter enforces its own timeout. `std::time::Duration` addition panics on overflow, so an extreme timeout value can turn a normal invocation path into a process panic. Replacing it with `saturating_add` removes that failure mode with effectively no behavioral downside."},{"amendment_id":"fr-13-43e2123e","decision":"accept","rationale":"`ManagedChild::send_signal` sends signals to the immediate PID only, `force_kill` delegates to that on Unix, and the spawn path does not place the child in a separate process group or Windows job. That means timeout/cancel can reap only the top-level child while grandchildren survive, so the current hard-timeout path does not reliably terminate the backend invocation it started. Treating the whole subprocess tree as the kill unit is the correct fix."},{"amendment_id":"fr-13-997cd9b5","decision":"accept","rationale":"The engine persists the snapshot as `RunStatus::Running` before invocation, then on a retryable failure appends `stage_failed` and may sleep for backoff without persisting any resumable state. `run resume` explicitly rejects `Running` snapshots. If the worker dies during that backoff window, the journal shows a retryable failure but the snapshot still claims an active run, leaving the project stuck. Persisting a resumable retry state, or teaching resume to recover stale `Running` snapshots, is necessary."}]}